lobal history? Bohlman uses the mode of translation to explore Herder’s own interpretive practice as a translator of languages and cultures, providing today’s readers with an elegantly narrated and exceptionally curated collection of essays on music by two major intellectuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aFolk songsxHistory and criticism. 0aNational characteristics. 0aNationalism in music. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aaesthetics.  aanalytical.  achristian influence.  achristian.  achristianity.  acomposer.  aculture.  aessays.  aethnomusicologist.  aglobal history.  aintellectual.  ajohann gottfried herder.  alanguage translation.  alanguage.  amusic theory.  amusical composition.  amusician.  anationalism.  areligion.  areligious studies.  areligious thought.  asacred music.  asacred songs.  ascholarly.  avolkslieder.1 aBohlman, Philip V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052023494940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966444/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles